WEBVTT

00:04.504 --> 00:06.293
<i>Previously on</i> Madam Secretary...

00:06.294 --> 00:08.077
HENRY: <i>I'm offering you a chance</i>

00:08.077 --> 00:09.183
to save your sister's life.

00:09.184 --> 00:11.602
Oh, my God. You, you are
asking me to be a spy.

00:11.603 --> 00:13.303
You know what they do
to spies in Russia?

00:13.813 --> 00:14.732
Please, get me out!

00:14.733 --> 00:15.982
HENRY: I'm taking care of it.

00:15.983 --> 00:17.142
Now, hang up the damn phone.

00:17.143 --> 00:19.192
There he is.

00:19.193 --> 00:20.313
Abort! Abort! Abort!

00:20.314 --> 00:21.432
What? No. What...?

00:21.433 --> 00:23.142
HENRY: Stop the van. Stop the van!

00:23.143 --> 00:24.432
Did you just give him up?

00:24.433 --> 00:25.812
Who's part of the negotiation?

00:25.813 --> 00:27.982
<i>Tell me where my brother is.</i>

00:27.983 --> 00:28.812
How do you sleep at night?

00:28.813 --> 00:30.036
HENRY: <i>Everything in my power.</i>

00:30.037 --> 00:30.873
How do you sleep...?

00:30.874 --> 00:31.993
(tires squealing)

00:33.313 --> 00:35.312
(laughter in distance)

00:35.313 --> 00:37.793
(indistinct chatter and laughter)

00:40.393 --> 00:42.352
ELIZABETH: Hey, good
morning, sleepyhead.

00:42.353 --> 00:43.438
Good morning, family.

00:43.439 --> 00:44.522
Morning, Dad.

00:44.523 --> 00:46.445
- I guess my alarm didn't go off.
- STEVIE: Yeah.

00:46.446 --> 00:48.192
My alarm sometimes does that, too.

00:48.193 --> 00:49.732
When I forget to set it.

00:49.733 --> 00:52.306
Uh, well, I guess that's possible.

00:52.307 --> 00:53.274
I was up kind of late.

00:53.275 --> 00:56.473
Yeah, followed by a fair
amount of tossing and turning.

00:56.474 --> 00:58.119
You see, that is why I never read

00:58.120 --> 01:00.079
classified documents before bed.

01:00.080 --> 01:01.789
All that catastrophic thinking

01:01.790 --> 01:03.213
kind of messes with the beta waves.

01:03.214 --> 01:05.289
So just to be safe,
you avoid thinking altogether?

01:05.290 --> 01:06.347
Glad you got up?

01:06.348 --> 01:08.289
Hey, aren't you supposed to
be on your way to New York?

01:08.290 --> 01:10.010
(muffled, indistinct):
Yeah... five minutes.

01:10.011 --> 01:11.354
ALISON: You're going to New York?

01:11.355 --> 01:12.709
Nobody tells me anything.

01:12.710 --> 01:15.039
I'm just going for the day.

01:15.040 --> 01:18.119
I'm giving a speech to
the UN General Assembly,

01:18.120 --> 01:21.579
asking them to formally
condemn Hizb al-Shahid.

01:21.580 --> 01:23.419
What's that going to do?

01:23.420 --> 01:27.749
Well, it's the diplomat's way
of saying to the school bully,

01:27.750 --> 01:30.079
"You know, everybody hates you."

01:30.080 --> 01:32.419
Your first speech to the UN, though.

01:32.420 --> 01:34.709
That's kind of cool. And historic.

01:34.710 --> 01:35.315
(clears throat)

01:35.316 --> 01:35.919
And...

01:35.920 --> 01:37.362
- tweetable.
- Yeah. Are you nervous?

01:37.363 --> 01:38.709
Well, I wasn't,

01:38.710 --> 01:40.919
so let's definitely
keep talking about it.

01:40.920 --> 01:43.789
Mm! Oh.

01:43.790 --> 01:46.209
Could you stop at the Hello
Kitty store in Times Square

01:46.210 --> 01:47.553
and get me this cute pencil case?

01:47.554 --> 01:48.709
It's an exclusive.

01:48.710 --> 01:50.119
Mom has a motorcade.

01:50.120 --> 01:52.879
She can't just stop by anywhere.

01:52.880 --> 01:55.329
Put it on your birthday list.

01:55.330 --> 01:56.960
Is Hello Kitty still in?

01:56.961 --> 01:57.916
Oh... (scoffs).

01:57.917 --> 02:00.379
Hello Kitty is the Chanel of our time.

02:00.380 --> 02:01.676
It'll never be out.

02:01.677 --> 02:03.804
That's just a little bit depressing.

02:03.805 --> 02:04.748
Oh, hey, wait a second.

02:04.749 --> 02:06.560
Before everybody scatters, listen:

02:06.561 --> 02:09.139
I got a call last night from
Mitch, and the horses

02:09.140 --> 02:12.430
are coming home from the winter
boarding stables this weekend.

02:12.431 --> 02:13.770
- Oh, cool.
- That's nice.

02:13.771 --> 02:15.180
I know. So I thought

02:15.181 --> 02:17.970
that maybe we could all go up on
Saturday and welcome them back.

02:17.971 --> 02:19.520
It would be like old times.

02:19.521 --> 02:21.730
We can ride a little bit,

02:21.731 --> 02:23.140
pop some popcorn.

02:23.141 --> 02:24.451
Cuddle by the fire.

02:27.101 --> 02:30.230
Okay, I realize I'm not Oprah
giving away free cars,

02:30.231 --> 02:31.774
but a little enthusiasm would be nice.

02:31.775 --> 02:34.230
It's just Jareth got us tickets

02:34.231 --> 02:36.100
to the symphony on Saturday night.

02:36.101 --> 02:37.964
And it's Molly's birthday
sleep-over. Remember?

02:37.965 --> 02:39.680
I just don't wanna.

02:39.681 --> 02:41.680
HENRY: Well, hey, I'm in.

02:41.681 --> 02:43.560
Riding, corn, cuddling, the whole deal.

02:43.561 --> 02:46.100
Romantic weekend it is,
just you and me.

02:46.101 --> 02:47.484
JASON: Oh, yeah, just you and Dad,

02:47.485 --> 02:50.060
and your true love... Buttercup.

02:50.061 --> 02:50.916
Aw.

02:50.917 --> 02:51.770
Oh, come on.

02:51.771 --> 02:53.434
- Not gonna fool me...
- STEVIE: Admit it.

02:53.435 --> 02:56.230
The only reason you want to go
up to the farm this weekend,

02:56.231 --> 02:58.020
is because Buttercup is coming home.

02:58.021 --> 02:59.140
What can I say?

02:59.141 --> 03:02.350
It's been a very long winter,
and I miss my horse.

03:02.351 --> 03:04.390
Buttercup. What a good boy.

03:04.391 --> 03:05.970
Buttercup has a clock in his head.

03:05.971 --> 03:08.520
He can do the course in perfect time.

03:08.521 --> 03:11.680
Don't forget how he
runs across the pasture

03:11.681 --> 03:12.810
whenever he sees me.

03:12.811 --> 03:14.234
JASON: He's an angel on this earth.

03:14.235 --> 03:16.180
STEVIE (laughs):
And he moves like a cat.

03:16.181 --> 03:18.100
The way he transitions into a canter,

03:18.101 --> 03:19.100
it's like... like...

03:19.101 --> 03:21.831
STEVIE & ALISON: Floating on air!

03:26.231 --> 03:27.951
(knocking on door, door opens)

03:29.731 --> 03:31.640
Dr. McCord.

03:31.641 --> 03:33.930
I did not realize you knew
where my office was.

03:33.931 --> 03:35.180
Yeah, I do.

03:35.181 --> 03:36.284
Uh, I need a favor, Oliver.

03:36.285 --> 03:37.890
Oh, I serve at the pleasure.

03:37.891 --> 03:39.474
Well, it's not Murphy Station business.

03:39.475 --> 03:40.640
It's about an old student.

03:40.641 --> 03:42.680
Uh, actually, his sister.

03:42.681 --> 03:44.970
Uh, I just want to check up on her.

03:44.971 --> 03:46.730
I do checkups. Name?

03:46.731 --> 03:47.970
Talia Petrov.

03:47.971 --> 03:50.270
P-E-T-R-O-V.

03:50.271 --> 03:52.031
M-O-U-S-E. (weak chuckle)

03:55.471 --> 03:56.730
Location?

03:56.731 --> 03:58.474
The last I heard, she
was leaving Stockholm,

03:58.475 --> 04:01.060
where she was in a drug
trial for fibrosarcoma.

04:01.061 --> 04:03.310
On her way back to Murom, Russia.

04:03.311 --> 04:05.600
I just want to make sure she's okay.

04:05.601 --> 04:06.930
Copy that.

04:06.931 --> 04:09.060
I will text you when I have a workup.

04:09.061 --> 04:10.911
Thank you.

04:13.181 --> 04:14.600
ELIZABETH: <i>The terrorist group</i>

04:14.601 --> 04:18.100
Hizb al-Shahid has only been
in existence for a short time,

04:18.101 --> 04:21.140
but it has already
perpetrated countless

04:21.141 --> 04:23.140
acts of of violence across the globe,

04:23.141 --> 04:25.060
including setting off

04:25.061 --> 04:27.430
a dirty bomb in Virginia.

04:27.431 --> 04:31.230
My family was at ground
zero during the attack,

04:31.231 --> 04:34.140
and because of that, I wondered
if I was the right person

04:34.141 --> 04:37.100
to stand here today
and ask for your help.

04:37.101 --> 04:40.100
Is it too personal?

04:40.101 --> 04:43.390
And then I realized, yes,

04:43.391 --> 04:45.350
it is personal to me,

04:45.351 --> 04:49.060
and to every single one of us.

04:49.061 --> 04:53.180
Because the principle at the
core of the United Nations

04:53.181 --> 04:57.430
is that all peoples, regardless
of race, color or creed,

04:57.431 --> 05:01.430
deserve to live lives of peace,

05:01.431 --> 05:05.140
free from the tyranny
of sudden violence.

05:05.141 --> 05:10.180
The challenge before us is enormous.

05:10.181 --> 05:12.470
But the struggle begins with words.

05:12.471 --> 05:17.100
That's why I'm here today
to ask for your solidarity

05:17.101 --> 05:20.310
and your resolve in
condemning this organization

05:20.311 --> 05:22.491
and everything it stands for.

05:23.971 --> 05:25.640
Shoulder to shoulder,

05:25.641 --> 05:28.520
we can bring the sponsors of terror

05:28.521 --> 05:32.890
to a swift and lasting justice.

05:32.891 --> 05:34.201
Thank you.

